## DBsubject('Precalculus')
## DBchapter('Exponential Functions')
## DBsection('Review Exercises and Problems')
## KEYWORDS('exponential functions','growth rate','growth factor','continuous exponential growth','e','compound interest','graphs of exponential functions')
## TitleText1('Functions Modeling Change')
## EditionText1('3')
## AuthorText1('Connally')
## Section1('3.Review')
## Problem1('10')
## Author('Adam Spiegler')
## Institution('Loyola University Chicago')

DOCUMENT();       

loadMacros("PG.pl",
           "PGbasicmacros.pl",
           "PGchoicemacros.pl",
           "PGanswermacros.pl",
           "PGgraphmacros.pl",
           "extraAnswerEvaluators.pl",
           "PGauxiliaryFunctions.pl",
           "PGgraphmacros.pl"
           );
       
TEXT(beginproblem()); # standard preamble to each problem.

$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

$a = random(200,900,25);
$m_a = random(40,80,5);
$r_b = random(7,12,1);
$dec_b = $r_b/100;
$fact_b = 1+$dec_b;
$m_d = random(10,30,2);
$r_e = random(3,6,1);
$dec_e = -$r_e/100;
$fact_e = 1+$dec_e;

$ans_a = "$a+$m_a t";
$ans_b = "$a*($fact_b)^t";
$ans_c = "$a*e^($dec_b t)";
$ans_d = "$a-$m_d t";
$ans_e = "$a*($fact_e)^t";
$ans_f = "$a*e^($dec_e t)";

BEGIN_TEXT
Question 10:
$BR $SPACE $BR
A town has population $a people at year $BITALIC t $EITALIC = 0.
Write a formula for the population, $BITALIC P${EITALIC}, in year $BITALIC t $EITALIC if the town
$BR $SPACE $BR
a) Grows by $m_a people per year. $SPACE $SPACE \( P = \) \{ans_rule(20) \}
$BR $SPACE $BR
b) Grows by $r_b$PERCENT per year. $SPACE $SPACE \( P = \) \{ans_rule(20) \}
$BR $SPACE $BR
c) Grows at a continuous rate of $r_b$PERCENT per year. $SPACE $SPACE \( P = \) \{ans_rule(20) \}
$BR $SPACE $BR
d) Shrinks by $m_d people per year. $SPACE $SPACE \( P = \) \{ans_rule(20) \}
$BR $SPACE $BR
e) Shrinks by $r_e$PERCENT per year. $SPACE $SPACE \( P = \) \{ans_rule(20) \}
$BR $SPACE $BR
f) Shrinks at a continuous rate of $r_e$PERCENT per year. $SPACE $SPACE \( P = \) \{ans_rule(20) \}

END_TEXT


ANS(fun_cmp($ans_a,vars=>'t') );
ANS(fun_cmp($ans_b,vars=>'t') );
ANS(fun_cmp($ans_c,vars=>'t') );
ANS(fun_cmp($ans_d,vars=>'t') );
ANS(fun_cmp($ans_e,vars=>'t') );
ANS(fun_cmp($ans_f,vars=>'t') );


SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION'));
$BR $SPACE $BR 
$BBOLD  SOLUTION $EBOLD
$BR 
If the population is growing or shrinking at a constant rate of $BITALIC m $EITALIC people per year, the formula is linear.  Since the vertical intercept is $a, we have \( P = $a + m t \).
$BR $SPACE $BR
If the population is growing or shrinking at a constant percent rate of $BITALIC r $EITALIC percent per year, the formula is exponential in the form \( P = a(1+r)^t \). Since the vertical intercept is $a, we have \( P = $a (1+ r)^t \).
$BR $SPACE $BR
If the population is growing or shrinking at a constant continuous percent rate of $BITALIC k $EITALIC percent per year, the formula is exponential in the form \( P = ae^{kt} \).  Since the vertical intercept is $a,  we have \( P = $a e^{kt}. \)
$BR $SPACE $BR
We have: $BR
$SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE a) \( P = $a + $m_a t \) $BR
$SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE b) \( P = $a($fact_b)^t \) $BR
$SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE c) \( P = $a e^{$dec_b t} \) $BR
$SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE d) \( P = $a - $m_d t \) $BR
$SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE e) \( P = $a($fact_e)^t \)$BR
$SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE f) \( P = $a e^{$dec_e t} \)
$BR
END_SOLUTION


ENDDOCUMENT();   # This should be the last executable line in the problem.